HEADWORD: Raspberry
<hw>Rasp"ber*ry</hw> <pr>(r⟦acr⟧z"b⟦ecr⟧r*r⟦ycr⟧; 277)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From E. <ets>rasp</ets>, in allusion to the apparent
roughness of the fruit.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The
thimble-shaped fruit of the <spn>Rubus Idaeus</spn> and other similar
brambles; <as>as, the black, the red, and the white
<ex>raspberry</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The shrub bearing this
fruit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Technically, raspberries are those brambles in which the
fruit separates readily from the core or receptacle, in this differing
from the blackberries, in which the fruit is firmly attached to the
receptacle.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rasper</ent>⟦br⟧
